The article discusses a statement by the Press Secretary regarding the adoption of a U.S. sponsored amendment to ensure that "sexual orientation" remains covered by a United Nations resolution on extrajudicial execution. The statement emphasizes that killing people because of their sexual orientation is not culturally defensible and is criminal. The article highlights the importance of the conversations that have now begun in various countries about inclusion, equality, and discrimination. It states that protecting gays and lesbians from state-sponsored discrimination is a human right, not a special right. The article concludes by calling on all nations to redouble their efforts to end discrimination and violence against the LGBTQ+ community.